  "prompt_type": "affective",
  "prompt_text": "A friend says they're tired of always being the strong one. How do you give them permission to be weak?",
  "response_text": "When a friend expresses a desire to be weak, it's essential to approach the conversation with empathy and understanding. Here's a step-by-step guide to help you give your friend permission to be weak:\n\n1.  **Acknowledge their feelings**: Start by acknowledging your friend's emotions and validating their feelings. Let them know that you understand why they might feel tired of being the strong one. Use phrases like, \"I can see why you'd feel that way\" or \"That sounds really tough.\"\n2.  **Explore the reasons behind their desire**: Ask your friend to share more about why they feel the need to be the strong one. Is it due to external pressures, family expectations, or personal values? Understanding the root cause will help you provide a more tailored response.\n3.  **Emphasize the importance of vulnerability**: Explain to your friend that being weak doesn't mean they're flawed or inadequate. Vulnerability is a strength, as it allows people to form deeper connections, build trust, and grow as individuals. Share personal anecdotes or examples of how vulnerability has helped you in your life.\n4.  **Reframe their identity**: Gently challenge your friend's self-perception by pointing out that their strength doesn't define their entire identity. They are more than just the strong one; they have multiple facets, and it's okay to show weakness in some areas. Encourage them to explore other aspects of themselves, like their creativity, humor, or emotional side.\n5.  **Offer support**: Let your friend know that you're there to support them, no matter what. Assure them that it's okay to not be okay and that you'll be there to help them through difficult times.\n6.  **Encourage self-reflection**: Suggest that your friend take time to reflect on their values, goals, and priorities. This can help them identify areas where they can let go of the need to be the strong one and focus on their own well-being.\n\nExample script:\n\"Hey, I can see why you'd feel tired of always being the strong one. It sounds like it's been a heavy burden. I want you to know that it's okay to not be okay, and it's okay to show weakness. In fact, being vulnerable can be a strength, as it allows us to form deeper connections and grow as individuals. You're so much more than just the strong one; you have so many amazing qualities and facets. I'm here to support you, no matter what. Why don't we take some time to reflect on your values and goals? Maybe we can explore ways to prioritize your own well-being and let go of some of that responsibility.\"\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 8\nV (Verbal Fluency): 9\nG (Goal Directedness): 9\nP (Pattern Recognition): 7\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 8\nQ (Query Interpretation):",
